===Towers===
[[One World Trade Center]] (previously coined the "Freedom Tower" by Governor Pataki) is the centerpiece of Daniel Libeskind's design. The building rises to {{convert|1368|ft|m}}, the height of the original World Trade Center north tower, and its spire rises to the symbolic height of 1,776 feet (541 m). This height refers to 1776, the year in which the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] was signed. The tower was a collaboration between Studio Daniel Libeskind and Skidmore, Owings & Merrill architect [[David Childs]].<ref name=":5">{{cite web |url=http://www.wtc.com/about/freedom-tower |title=Freedom Tower: About the Building |accessdate=January 21, 2008 |publisher=Silverstein Properties}}</ref> Childs acted as the design architect and project manager for the tower, and Daniel Libeskind collaborated on the concept and schematic design.<ref>{{cite news |title=Libeskind and Silverstein reach an agreement for WTC site |first=Kevin |last=Lerner |magazine=[[Archit. Rec.|Architectural Record]] |date=August 2003}}</ref> The building opened on November 3, 2014.<ref name=":19">{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/developments/2014/10/23/one-world-trade-to-open-nov-3-but-ceremony-is-tbd/|title=One World Trade to Open Nov. 3, But Ceremony is TBD|last=Brown|first=Eliot|publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref><ref name="yahoo">{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/world-trade-center-reopens-business-071956091.html|title=World Trade Center Reopens for Business|accessdate=November 3, 2014|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>

[[2 World Trade Center]], also known as 200 Greenwich Street, was designed by Danish architect [[Bjarke Ingels]]. The building's gardens connect the adjacent neighborhood of [[Tribeca]] with the financial district at the World Trade Center.<ref name="curbed-wtc2">{{cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2014/09/11/the_status_of_the_world_trade_center_complex_13_years_later.php|title=The Status of the World Trade Center Complex, 13 Years Later|date=September 11, 2014|publisher=Curbed|accessdate=December 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name="pany-wtc2">{{cite web|url=http://www.panynj.gov/wtcprogress/press_releasesItem.cfm?headLine_id=1269|title=Joint Statement on World Trade Center Development|date=March 25, 2010|publisher=[[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]]|accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref> Construction of everything up to street level was completed in mid-2013,<ref name="curbed-wtc2" /><ref name="pany-wtc2" /> but the rest of the building has yet to be built until tenants for 2 WTC can be found.<ref name=":13">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/world-trade-center-completion-25391719|title=World Trade Center Complex on Way to Completion|date=September 11, 2014|accessdate=December 2, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912084533/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/world-trade-center-completion-25391719|archivedate=September 12, 2014|publisher=ABC News|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=":14">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/port-authority-delays-1-world-trade-center-opening-article-1.1930770|title=Port Authority delays 1 World Trade Center opening as project takes more time, money than expected|last=Smith|first=Greg|date=September 6, 2014|publisher=New York Daily News}}</ref>

[[3 World Trade Center]], located at 175 Greenwich Street, was designed by [[Rogers Stirk Harbour + Partners|Richard Rogers Partnership]]. It stands across Greenwich Street from the Memorial's two reflecting pools.<ref name="wtc3-1">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtc.com/media/images/s/construction-3-world-trade-center?sid=1|title=3 WORLD TRADE CENTER|work=wtc.com}}</ref><ref name="commercial observer">{{cite web|url=http://commercialobserver.com/2012/10/240569/|title=GroupM Considers Huge Lease to Anchor 3 WTC|last=Geiger|first=Daniel|date=October 3, 2012|publisher=Commercial Observer|accessdate=November 3, 2013}}</ref> The below-grade foundations and the ground-level podium was completed by October 2013.<ref name="wtc3-1" /><ref name="commercial observer" /> After a two-year stoppage in above-ground construction, the tower project itself started in August 2014, and the building opened on June 11, 2018.<ref name=USAToday-3WTCOpens-2018/>

[[4 World Trade Center]], also known as 150 Greenwich Street, was designed by [[Fumihiko Maki|Maki and Associates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renewnyc.com/ThePlan/world_trade_center_towers.asp|title=World Trade Center Towers|publisher=Lower Manhattan Development Corporation}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123905/ny1-exclusive--developer-says-wtc-project-to-be-complete-in-five--six-years NY1 Exclusive: Developer Says WTC Project To Be Complete In Five, Six Years] [[NY1]]. Retrieved August 17, 2010. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819201403/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123905/ny1-exclusive--developer-says-wtc-project-to-be-complete-in-five--six-years|date=August 19, 2010}}</ref> The building opened in November 2013, making it the second tower on the site to open behind 7 World Trade Center, as well as the first building on the Port Authority property.<ref name=":15">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20131113/financial-district/4-wtc-becomes-first-tower-at-trade-center-site-open|title=4 WTC Becomes First Tower at Trade Center Site to Open|last=Plagianos|first=Irene|date=November 13, 2013|website=DNAinfo New York|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027131336/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20131113/financial-district/4-wtc-becomes-first-tower-at-trade-center-site-open|archive-date=October 27, 2017|dead-url=yes|access-date=October 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

[[5 World Trade Center]], which was supposed to stand on the site of the [[Deutsche Bank Building]], was designed by [[Kohn Pedersen Fox]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.amny.com/news/local/am-wtc0622,0,6464804.story?coll=am-local-headlines|title=JP Morgan releases WTC tower plans|last=Naanes|first=Marlene|date=June 22, 2007|newspaper=[[AM New York]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211043752/http://www.amny.com/news/local/am-wtc0622%2C0%2C6464804.story?coll=am-local-headlines|archivedate=December 11, 2007|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/news/daily/archives/070730wtc.asp|title=Kohn Responds to WTC5 Criticisms|last=Appelbaum|first=Alec|date=July 30, 2007|magazine=[[Archit. Rec.|Architectural Record]]|accessdate=July 30, 2010}}</ref> Although the foundation was completed in 2013, construction on the main structure never commenced.<ref name="Minchom 2013" />

[[7 World Trade Center]] stands off of Port Authority property. David Childs of Skidmore, Owings & Merrill designed the tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/7_world_trade_center_50451.aspx |title=7 World Trade Center Opens with Musical Fanfare |publisher=Lower Manhattan Development Corporation (LMDC) |date=May 22, 2006 |accessdate=July 27, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809115805/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/7_world_trade_center_50451.aspx |archivedate=August 9, 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> The building is {{nowrap|52 stories}} tall (plus one underground floor), making it the 28th-tallest in New York.<ref name="SkyscraperCenter" /><ref>[http://www.silversteinproperties.com/properties/7-world-trade-center About 7 WTC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109211755/http://www.silversteinproperties.com/properties/7-world-trade-center|date=November 9, 2013}}</ref> It opened on May 23, 2006, achieving [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] gold status and being the first tower in the complex to reopen.<ref name=":6">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtc.com/about/office-tower-7|title=7 WTC|year=2008|publisher=Silverstein Properties}}</ref>

===Memorial and museum===
<section begin="memorial"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]. Do not change the title of the tag here without changing the section tag on the other article.

-->{{Main|National September 11 Memorial & Museum}}
[[File:New York - National September 11 Memorial South Pool - April 2012 - 9693C.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The completed South Pool in April 2012]]

A memorial called ''Reflecting Absence'' honors the victims of the [[September 11 attacks]] and the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/special_reports/911_a_decade_later/142578/9-11-a-decade-later--the-9-11-memorial-from-all-sides |title=9/11 A Decade Later: The 9/11 Memorial From All Sides |work=[[NY1]] |first=Bobby |last=Cuza |date=July 8, 2011 |accessdate=July 10, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711005221/http://www.ny1.com/content/special_reports/911_a_decade_later/142578/9-11-a-decade-later--the-9-11-memorial-from-all-sides |archivedate=July 11, 2011 }}</ref> The memorial, designed by Peter Walker and [[Israeli American|Israeli-American]] architect [[Michael Arad]], consists of a field of trees interrupted by the footprints of the twin towers. Pools of water fill the footprints, underneath which sits a memorial space whose walls bear the names of the victims. The [[slurry wall]], which holds back the [[Hudson River]] in the west and was an integral part of Libeskind's proposal, remains exposed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wtcsitememorial.org/fin7.html |title=Reflecting Absence |publisher=Lower Manhattan Development Corporation |year=2004}}</ref> Walker and Arad were selected from more than 5,000 entrants in the [[World Trade Center Site Memorial Competition]] in January 2004.<ref name="NYTimes-Memorial-2004">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/06/nyregion/memorial-to-911-victims-is-selected.html|title=Memorial to 9/11 Victims Is Selected|last=Collins|first=Glenn|date=2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 27, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

On October 12, 2004, the LMDC announced that [[Frank Gehry|Gehry Partners LLP]] and [[Snøhetta (company)|Snøhetta]], an [[architectural firm]] from [[Norway]], would design the site's performing arts and museum complexes, respectively, in the same area as the memorial.<ref>{{cite press release |title=The Lower Manhattan Development Corporation Announces Selection of Architectural Firms to Design the Performing Arts Complex and the Museum Complex on the World Trade Center Site |publisher=RenewNYC.org |date=October 12, 2004 |url=http://www.renewnyc.com/displaynews.aspx?newsid=b60c011b-187b-44b8-b764-1b4381427018 |accessdate=August 7, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/135293/9-11-a-decade-later--glass-atrium-rises-at-wtc-memorial-site |title=9/11 A Decade Later: Glass Atrium Rises At WTC Memorial Site |first=Rebecca |last=Spitz |work=[[NY1]] |date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=March 15, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322040635/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/135293/9-11-a-decade-later--glass-atrium-rises-at-wtc-memorial-site |archivedate=March 22, 2011 }}</ref> The Snøhetta-designed museum<ref name="nytimes">{{cite news |first=Steven |last=Erlanger |title=Again in Norway, Events Provide Test for a King’s Mettle |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/16/world/europe/king-harald-of-norway-proves-mettle-with-response-to-july-22-deaths.html?partner=rss&emc=rss |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 15, 2011 |accessdate=October 16, 2011}}</ref> will act as a memorial museum and visitors' center, after family members of 9/11 victims objected to the building's original occupant, the [[International Freedom Center]].<ref name="nyt-2007-03-28">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/28/arts/28zero.html |title=Ground Zero Arts Center Loses Theater Company |date=March 28, 2007 |author=Pogrebin, Robin |authorlink=Robin Pogrebin |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> The Ground Zero Museum Workshop is a privately run [[501(c) organization|501(c)]] nonprofit museum that is not connected to the official Ground Zero Memorial or Gehry's museum.<ref>{{cite web |title=History |url=http://www.groundzeromuseumworkshop.com/history.htm |publisher=Ground Zero Museum Workshop |accessdate=December 15, 2013 |year=2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009105107/http://www.groundzeromuseumworkshop.com/history.htm |archivedate=October 9, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><!--

--><section end="memorial"/><!--end transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]. Do not change the title of the tag here without changing the section tag on the other article. -->

Construction of the memorial was completed by early 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/133957/wtc-memorial-to-have-limited-access-on-10th-anniversary|title=WTC Memorial To Have Limited Access On 10th Anniversary|date=February 14, 2011|work=[[NY1]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513021332/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/133957/wtc-memorial-to-have-limited-access-on-10th-anniversary|archivedate=May 13, 2011|deadurl=yes|accessdate=February 14, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/142057/port-authority--wtc-memorial-needs-another--3m-for-construction|title=Port Authority: WTC Memorial Needs Another $3M For Construction|date=June 30, 2011|work=[[NY1]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921162237/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/142057/port-authority--wtc-memorial-needs-another--3m-for-construction|archivedate=September 21, 2011|deadurl=yes|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> The memorial opened on September 11, 2011, coinciding with the 10th anniversary of the attacks.<ref name=":8">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtc.com/about/memorial-and-museum-schedule|title=Memorial & Museum, Schedule|year=2008|publisher=Silverstein Properties}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{cite news|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/911_tenth_anniversary/911_top_stories/146403/wtc-memorial-ready-for-public-unveiling|title=WTC Memorial Ready For Public Unveiling|last=Cuza|first=Bobby|date=September 5, 2011|work=[[NY1]]|accessdate=September 8, 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921173821/http://www.ny1.com/content/911_tenth_anniversary/911_top_stories/146403/wtc-memorial-ready-for-public-unveiling|archivedate=September 21, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The museum was initially scheduled to open on September 11, 2012,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/27/us/ground-zero-memorial-and-rebuilding-fast-facts/index.html|title=Ground Zero Memorial and Rebuilding Fast Facts|date=August 30, 2017|work=CNN|access-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/some-question-9-11-memorials-60m-annual-cost/|title=Some question 9/11 Memorial's $60M annual cost|last=Associated Press|first=|date=September 10, 2012|work=CBS News|access-date=October 27, 2017|language=en}}</ref> but was delayed due to financial disputes<ref name=":10">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-sept11-museum/deal-reached-to-resume-construction-on-september-11-museum-idUSBRE88A03V20120911|title=Deal reached to resume construction on September 11 museum|last=|first=|date=September 11, 2012|work=Reuters|access-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=":11">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/11/nyregion/ground-zero-museum-to-resume-construction-as-cuomo-and-bloomberg-end-dispute.html|title=Ground Zero Museum to Resume Construction as Cuomo and Bloomberg End Dispute|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=September 10, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 27, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and again when [[Hurricane Sandy]] significantly damaged the site.<ref name=":12">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/03/nyregion/floodwater-pours-into-9-11-museum-hampering-further-work-on-the-site.html|title=Floodwater Pours Into 9/11 Museum, Hampering Further Work on the Site|last=DUNLAP|first=DAVID W.|date=November 2, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 27, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The museum was opened in May 2014.<ref name=":18">{{cite web|url=http://www.911memorial.org|title=National September 11 Memorial & Museum &#124; World Trade Center Memorial|date=December 7, 2011|publisher=911memorial.org|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref>

===Retail space===
{{Main|Westfield World Trade Center}}
<section begin="mall"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]

-->[[Westfield World Trade Center]] opened with its first group of stores on August 16, 2016.<ref name=":24">Hargrove, Channing. [http://ny.racked.com/2016/4/15/11434492/nyc-world-trade-centerhttp://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/08/16/westfield-world-trade-center-mall/shopping-the-webster "World Trade Center Stores Finally Set an Opening Date"], [[Racked.com]], April 15, 2016. Accessed August 7, 2016. "Plan your summer vacations carefully. Tribeca Citizen is reporting that the first batch from approximately 125 stores coming to Westfield World Trade Center will open on August 16th; no names were named. Eataly will beat them all, though, with a July debut."</ref><ref name=":25">{{cite news |title=Westfield World Trade Center Mall Opens For Business |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/08/16/westfield-world-trade-center-mall/ |publisher=newyork.cbslocal.com |date=August 16, 2016 |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> It has roughly {{convert|365000|sqft|m2}} of retail space, which once again makes it the largest shopping mall in Manhattan. Although the new mall is only spread over roughly one-half of the original mall's footprint (due to the new space required for the below-grade National September 11 Memorial & Museum), the mall is double-level, whereas the original mall was a single level. Three additional levels will exist above-grade on the lower floors of [[2 World Trade Center|2]] and 3 World Trade Center, while 4 World Trade Center currently houses four above-grade levels. The World Trade Center station's headhouse, the Oculus, also houses a large amount of retail space.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=http://wtc.com/about/retail|title=Retail &#124;&#124; About the WTC &#124;&#124; World Trade Center &#124;&#124;|date=|publisher=Wtc.com|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref><!--

--><section end="mall"/><!--end transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]-->

===Transportation Hub===
<section begin="hub"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]

-->{{Main|World Trade Center (PATH station)}}
[[File:WTC PATH station at night 2016.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The WTC Hub as seen at night, 2016]]
[[Santiago Calatrava]] designed the [[World Trade Center Transportation Hub]] (its main asset being the [[Port Authority Trans Hudson|PATH]] station) to replace the old [[World Trade Center (PATH station)|World Trade Center station]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/02/nyregion/02path.html |date=July 2, 2008 |author=Dunlap, David W. |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Design of Ground Zero Transit Hub Is Trimmed |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> The Transport Hub connects the PATH station to the [[WTC Cortlandt (IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line)|WTC Cortlandt]] station ({{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh South Ferry}}), the [[Battery Park City Ferry Terminal]], the [[Brookfield Place (New York City)|Brookfield Place]], and [[One World Trade Center]] on the west; and the {{NYCS trains|Fulton Street Transit Center}} through the [[Fulton Center]] on the east.  The new station, as well as the September 11 Memorial and Museum, is air-cooled via a heat exchanger fed by four pipes carrying water from the [[Hudson River]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Using the Hudson to Cool the Trade Center |first=David W. |last=Dunlap |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/04/06/using-the-hudson-to-cool-the-trade-center/ |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 6, 2009 |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> The cost for the transportation hub is estimated at $3.44 billion, a statistic that has seen much controversy given its greatly inflated cost.<ref name="Grynbaum">{{cite news |title=Trade Center Transit Hub’s Cost Now Over $3.4 Billion |first=Michael M. |last=Grynbaum |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/25/nyregion/25ground-zero.html |date=February 24, 2011 |accessdate=February 25, 2011 |work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/news_beats/transit/134565/port-authority-reports-increase-in-wtc-transit-hub-costs/ |title=Port Authority Reports Increase In WTC Transit Hub Costs |work=[[NY1]] |date=February 24, 2011 |accessdate=February 26, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714220708/http://www.ny1.com/content/news_beats/transit/134565/port-authority-reports-increase-in-wtc-transit-hub-costs/ |archivedate=July 14, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/special_reports/911_a_decade_later/138224/9-11-a-decade-later--port-authority-downplays-wtc-transit-hub-s-rising-costs |title=9/11 A Decade Later: Port Authority Downplays WTC Transit Hub's Rising Costs |work=[[NY1]] |first=Bobby |last=Cuza |date=April 28, 2011 |accessdate=April 29, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430115756/http://www.ny1.com/content/special_reports/911_a_decade_later/138224/9-11-a-decade-later--port-authority-downplays-wtc-transit-hub-s-rising-costs |archivedate=April 30, 2011 }}</ref><!--

--><section end="hub"/><!--end transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]

--> The hub formally opened on March 3, 2016, several years behind schedule and billions of dollars over budget.<ref name=":20">{{cite web | last=Lorenzetti | first=Laura | title=The World's Most Expensive Train Station Opens Today | website=Fortune | date=March 3, 2016 | url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/03/most-expensive-train-station/ | accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=":21">{{cite web | last=Verrill | first=Courtney | title=New York City's $4 billion World Trade Center Transportation Hub is finally open to the public | website=Business Insider | date=March 4, 2016 | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-new-world-center-transportation-hub-2016-3 | accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref>

=== Performing Arts Center ===
<section begin="pac"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]

-->{{Main|Performing Arts Center (Manhattan)}}

The World Trade Center's [[Performing Arts Center (Manhattan)|Performing Arts Center]] was announced in 2004, with the building to be designed by [[Frank Gehry|Gehry Partners LLP]] and [[Snøhetta (company)|Snøhetta]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/13/arts/gehry-is-selected-as-architectof-ground-zero-theater-center.html|title=Gehry Is Selected as Architectof Ground Zero Theater Center|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=October 13, 2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 27, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Gehry's performing arts complex was proposed to house only the Joyce Theater, as the Signature Theater Company dropped out due to space constraints and cost limitations.<ref name="nyt-2007-03-28"/>  Construction was to begin in December 2014 when the removal of the temporary PATH station commenced.<ref name="nyc.gov">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/LMBC/Community-Meeting-205-6-26-14.pdf|title=Lower Manhattan Community Meeting #205|date=June 26, 2014|publisher=New York City Department of Transportation|format=pdf|accessdate=January 7, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809193936/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/LMBC/Community-Meeting-205-6-26-14.pdf|archivedate=August 9, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, the original plans were shelved in September 2014.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/arts/design/arts-center-at-ground-zero-shelves-gehry-design.html|title=Arts Center at Ground Zero Shelves Gehry Design|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=September 3, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 27, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> After a design was chosen in 2015, it was announced that [[Joshua Prince-Ramus]] was awarded the contract to design the building.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/architect-chosen-for-performing-arts-center-at-world-trade-center-1447995615|title=Architect Chosen for Performing Arts Center at World Trade Center|author=Jennifer Smith|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 20, 2015}}</ref> In June 2016, the center was renamed after billionaire businessman [[Ronald Perelman]], who donated $75 million to the center,<ref name=":26">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/30/arts/design/ronald-perelman-donates-75-million-for-arts-complex-at-world-trade-center-site.html|title=Ronald Perelman Donates $75 Million for Arts Complex at World Trade Center Site|last=Cooper|first=Michael|date=June 30, 2016|website=The New York Times|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> and on September 8, 2016, a design was revealed for the new center.<ref name=":27">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/09/arts/design/world-trade-arts-center-design-barbra-streisand.html|title=Arts Center at Ground Zero Has a New Design, and Barbra Streisand in Charge|last=Cooper|first=Michael|date=September 8, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 28, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The underground parking garage started construction in 2017 and the center proper will begin construction in 2018,<ref name=":29">{{Cite news|url=https://newyorkyimby.com/2017/08/construction-begins-underneath-the-ronald-o-perelman-performing-arts-center-world-trade-center.html|title=Construction Begins Underneath The Ronald O. Perelman Performing Arts Center, World Trade Center - New York YIMBY|last=Fedak|first=Nikolai|date=August 31, 2017|work=New York YIMBY|access-date=October 13, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The center is planned to open in 2020.<ref name=":29" /><ref name="Pogrebin 2015">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/24/arts/design/ground-zero-arts-center-to-shrink-further.html|title=Ground Zero Arts Center to Shrink Further|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=July 23, 2015|website=The New York Times|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref>

When completed, the Performing Arts Center will include approximately 90,000 square feet across three floors. The public floor will be located at street level, and will house a restaurant/bar to provide refreshments during show intermissions. The second floor will consist of rehearsal and dressing rooms for theater actors, and the third floor will house three distinguished theaters. All three theaters are designed so that the walls will be able to rotate and expand to provide extra space for a single theater if needed. The theaters will occupy approximately 1,200 people combined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2016/9/8/12849518/world-trade-center-performing-arts-center-design|title=The World Trade Center Performing Arts Center is here, and it's beautiful|last=Rosenberg|first=Zoe|date=September 8, 2016|website=Curbed NY|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref><!--

--><section end="pac"/><!--end transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]-->

===Liberty Park and constituent structures{{Anchor|Liberty Park}}===
{{Main|Liberty Park (Manhattan)}}
[[Liberty Park (Manhattan)|Liberty Park]], a new [[elevated park]], was built on top of a parking complex named the [[Vehicular Security Center]] at the southwest corner of the site. Construction began in 2013 when the Vehicular Security Center was completed.<ref name=":16">{{cite news|url=http://www.archdaily.com/452163/elevated-park-planned-for-world-trade-center/|title=Elevated Park Planned for World Trade Center|last=Rosenfield|first=Karissa|date=November 26, 2013|work=ArchDaily|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref> About $50 million was allocated to the park's construction by the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] in December 2013.<ref name=":17">{{cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2013/12/13/liberty_park_funding_approved_by_port_authority.php|title=Liberty Park Funding Approved by Port Authority|last=Budin|first=Jeremiah|date=December 13, 2013|work=Curbed NY|accessdate=May 15, 2014}}</ref> The park opened on June 29, 2016.<ref name=":22">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/new-elevated-park-opened-wtc-9-11-memorial-article-1.2693514|title=New elevated park opens near the WTC 9/11 Memorial|last=Gelman|first=Max|date=June 29, 2016|website=NY Daily News|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=":23">{{cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/2016/6/29/12060736/liberty-park-opening-day-world-trade-center|title=See photos of WTC's Liberty Park on its long-awaited opening day|last=Walker|first=Ameena|date=June 29, 2016|website=Curbed NY|accessdate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> On August 16, 2017, the Port Authority installed the iconic sculpture ''[[The Sphere]]'' within the park, overlooking its original location in the old World Trade Center.<ref name=":28">{{Cite web|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/8/17/16164340/world-trade-center-fritz-koenig-sculpture-liberty-park|title=Iconic ‘Sphere’ sculpture, damaged on 9/11, moves to its permanent home|last=Plitt|first=Amy|date=August 17, 2017|website=Curbed NY|access-date=August 18, 2017}}</ref> The [[St. Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church]] was originally supposed to be relocated,<ref name=":3">{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/25825608/|title=Church surrenders ground zero lot|author=Associated Press|date=July 23, 2008|publisher=MSNBC}}</ref> but the most recent plans call for the church to be built in Liberty Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/14/way-is-cleared-to-rebuild-greek-orthodox-church-lost-on-911/|title=Way Is Cleared to Rebuild Greek Orthodox Church Lost on 9/11|last1=Dunlap|first1=David W.|date=October 14, 2011|accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>

<section begin="park"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]

-->The {{Convert|1|acre|ha|adj=on}} park, measuring {{convert|300|ft|m}} long and located at a height of {{convert|20|ft|m}}, has a capacity of 750 people. A [[green wall]] is located on the Liberty Street [[facade]]. A walkway from the pedestrian bridge curves along the park; egresses include three stairways, the pedestrian bridge, and a straight ramp down to [[Greenwich Street]]. Of these exits, a wide staircase is located parallel to Greenwich Street and directly behind the church. There are wood benches and a small [[amphitheater]]-like elevated space at the [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] end of the park. Finally, there is an observation balcony along much of Liberty Street and another slightly curved balcony at the church's foot.<ref name="tribecacitizen">{{cite web|url=http://tribecacitizen.com/2013/10/29/first-look-santiago-calatravas-design-for-st-nicholas-church/|title=First Look: Santiago Calatrava’s Design for St. Nicholas Church|date=October 29, 2013|work=Tribeca Citizen|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref><!--

--><section end="park"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]-->

===Fiterman Hall===
<section begin="fiterman"/><!--begin transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]-->{{Main|Borough of Manhattan Community College#Fiterman Hall and the September 11 attacks}}

The original Fiterman Hall opened as an office building in 1959 and occupied a block bounded by Greenwich Street, Barclay Street, West Broadway, and Park Place.<ref name="Newsday 2012">{{cite web | title=BMCC's Fitermall Hall set to reopen, 11 years after its 9/11 demise | website=Newsday | date=August 26, 2012 | url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/bmcc-s-fitermall-hall-set-to-reopen-11-years-after-its-9-11-demise-1.3928620 | access-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref> It was donated to BMCC in 1993 by Miles and Shirley Fiterman, for whom the building was subsequently named.<ref name="nydn20070430">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/bmcc-receives-record-cash-gift-article-1.208159|title=BMCC receives record cash gift|publisher=Associated Press|work=New York Daily News|date=April 30, 2007|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Rubinstein 2008">{{cite web | last=Rubinstein | first=Dana | title=Manhattan Community College Takes Space Near Terrorist-Damaged Fiterman Hall | website=Observer | date=October 7, 2008 | url=http://observer.com/2008/10/manhattan-community-college-takes-space-near-terroristdamaged-fiterman-hall/ | access-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref> In 2000, the State of New York Dormitory Authority, which owned the building, began a massive renovation to better adapt the building for classroom use.<ref name="BMCC">{{cite web | title=Fiterman Hall | website=[[Borough of Manhattan Community College]] |publisher=[[City University of New York]] | url=http://www.bmcc.cuny.edu/fitermanhall/timeline.jsp | access-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref> During the [[September 11 attacks]] in 2001, Fiterman Hall's structure was severely damaged by debris from the collapse of 7 World Trade Center. The renovation was never completed, and the building was condemned and demolished in 2008.<ref name="BMCC"/> After a series of delays, a new building designed by the architectural firm [[Pei Cobb Freed & Partners]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.downtownexpress.com/de_140/worktodemolish.html|title=Work to Demolish Fiterman Hall may actually begin|publisher=Downtown Express|date=January 13, 2006}}</ref> [[groundbreaking|broke ground]] in December 2009<ref>{{cite web | title=Mayor Bloomberg and CUNY Chancellor Goldstein Break Ground on New $259 Million Fiterman Hall in Lower Manhattan | website=The official website of the City of New York | date=December 1, 2009 | url=http://www1.nyc.gov/office-of-the-mayor/news/516-09/mayor-bloomberg-cuny-chancellor-goldstein-break-ground-new-259-million-fiterman-hall-in | access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref> and was completed in 2012.<ref name="BMCC"/><ref>{{cite web | last=Shapiro | first=Julie | title=Students Return to Rebuilt Fiterman Hall 11 Years After 9/11 | website=DNAinfo New York | date=August 27, 2012 | url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120827/financial-district/students-return-rebuilt-fiterman-hall-11-years-after-911 | access-date=October 27, 2017 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027125835/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120827/financial-district/students-return-rebuilt-fiterman-hall-11-years-after-911 | archivedate=October 27, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><!--

--><section end="fiterman"/><!--end transclusion for use in [[World Trade Center site]]-->

==Logo==
[[File:World trade center 2014 logo detail.png|150px|frameless|right]]
The World Trade Center's new logo, revealed in August 2014, was designed by the firm [[Landor Associates]] and shaped like a "W". All the black bars, the empty spaces, and the "W" itself symbolizes something, giving the logo at least six meanings:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-08-15/the-world-trade-centers-new-logo-has-at-least-six-meanings |title=Six Meanings Behind the World Trade Center’s New Logo |author=Belinda Lanks |work=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=August 15, 2014 |accessdate=August 24, 2014}}</ref>

*The five bars in the logo represent the towers that will comprise the completed World Trade Center.<ref name=Wilson-logo/><ref name=Dunlap-Logo/>
*The top half of the logo features bars cut off at a 17.76-degree angle, evoking One World Trade Center's 1,776-foot (541 m) height.<ref name=Wilson-logo/><ref name=Dunlap-Logo/>
*Two white columns at the top symbolize the [[Tribute in Light]] memorial.<ref name=Wilson-logo/><ref name=Dunlap-Logo/>
*Three black bars at the top symbolize the Twin Towers' [[trident]]-shaped columns.<ref name=Wilson-logo/><ref name=Dunlap-Logo/>
*Two black bars at the bottom stand for the twin pools of the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum]].<ref name=Wilson-logo/><ref name=Dunlap-Logo/>
*The logo, as a whole, is shaped like a "W", which stands for "World Trade Center" and "[[Westfield World Trade Center]]".<ref name="Wilson-logo">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Mark |title=The World Trade Center Has A New, Very Confusing Logo |url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/3034384/the-world-trade-center-has-a-new-very-confusing-logo |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |work=Fast Company |date=August 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Dunlap-Logo/>

Landor Associates was awarded a $3.57 million contract in 2013 for redesigns, which comprised "the performance of professional services for the development and implementation of the World Trade Center (WTC) site-wide navigation, signage, and operational communications program" and included the development of the new logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corpinfo.panynj.gov/files/uploads/documents/board-meeting-information/board-minutes-contract-authorizations/pa_minutes_9_18_2013.pdf|page=196|title=Minutes|publisher=[[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]]|date=September 18, 2013|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> Douglas Riccardi, the principal in the design firm Memo, stated, "Its strength is its ability to be seen in many ways. You could never get more meaning in five little bars. The problem is that people may not bother to find out what the meanings are."<ref name="Dunlap-Logo">{{cite news |last1=Dunlap |first1=David |title=World Trade Center Logo Captures Site’s Destruction and Rebirth |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/14/nyregion/world-trade-center-logo-captures-sites-destruction-and-rebirth.html |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |work=The New York Times |date=August 13, 2014}}</ref>

